    excerpt:
      "A house rises from bricks and stone, / but a home— / a home is born from the warm faces",
    full: `A house rises from bricks and stone,
but a home—
a home is born from the warm faces
that pour their tenderness into its walls.

Yet the moment the breath of relationships begins to fade,
when laughter escapes
and buries itself in some distant silence,
the home trembles…
and slowly dissolves
like a spirit losing its last light.

When bonds break,
they make no sound—
but the air changes its color.
A cold poison settles into every corner,
turning familiar rooms
into strangers
and shadows into wounds.

And when the elders leave this world…
the true darkness begins.
For it was their presence—
their gentle scolding,
their quiet blessings—
that held the pulsing heart
of that fragile home.

After they are gone,
people no longer divide love…
they divide rooms, walls, and belongings.
Where prayers once slept,
locks now hang;
and the room that once echoed with laughter
lies still—
the corpse of a memory.

The truth stands unshaken—
a home was never made of walls.
It was woven from the people
whose warmth softened every pain,
whose presence filled every breath
with grace and tenderness.

And when those souls leave forever,
we finally understand—
the house has returned
to what it once was:
a cold, hollow structure,
stripped of light,
stripped of love,
stripped of the reason
to be called a home.`,
