    id: 54,
    title: "“The Night Remembers Everything”",
    excerpt:
      "I no longer wonder / whether I’ll forgive them— / forgiveness is a luxury",
    full: `I no longer wonder
whether I’ll forgive them—
forgiveness is a luxury
reserved for the living.
And a part of me
died the day they chose
to break what they did not build.

Maybe I’ll forgive.
Maybe I won’t.
But karma…
karma has a memory
far sharper than mine.

Those who wound innocent hearts
do not walk away clean—
they walk away cursed,
haunted by the very pain
they once smiled at
while inflicting.

Life is not merciful
to those who are merciless.
It waits in silence,
like a predator in the dark,
studying their steps,
marking their sins.

Let them run.
Let them hide.
The night will still find them.

For poison grows
only where poison is planted.
For shadows cling
only to those who summon them.

Their karma will not knock—
it will break their door.
It will drag them
through the same fire
they once pushed me into.

And when they scream,
they will finally understand
the weight of what they’ve done.

Because in the end,
no sinner escapes the echo
of their own cruelty.
The universe always returns
what they tried to bury.

Always.`,
