    id: 264,
    title: "PART 3 OF 5 POTERY",
    excerpt: `"The Soil Remembers Warmth" / I did not wake up healed. / Healing does not arrive like morning.`,
    full: `"The Soil Remembers Warmth"

I did not wake up healed.
Healing does not arrive like morning.
It came the way thaw comes—
without announcement,
without certainty,
only a slight change
in how the ground responded to weight.

Something shifted.

Not enough to name,
not enough to trust,
but enough to notice
that standing still
did not hurt as much as before.

The land around me was the same—
same trees, same silence,
same unanswered skies—
yet my body began to listen differently.
Pain, once sharp,
had softened into pressure,
like a hand resting
instead of gripping.

I found myself watching light again.
Not chasing it,
not asking it to stay—
just acknowledging its presence
when it slipped through branches
and touched the earth without expectation.

The soil, I realized, remembers warmth.
Even after frost,
it keeps the knowledge of spring
buried deep,
waiting for permission
to respond.

I did not forgive everything.
I did not forget.
Some losses are permanent structures—
they shape the land.
But I stopped defending my wounds
as if they were the only proof
that I had loved honestly.

Rain fell one afternoon,
soft, undecided.
For the first time,
I did not turn away.
I let it reach me,
not as cleansing,
but as contact—
a reminder that touch
does not always demand return.

At night,
the darkness loosened its grip.
It no longer pressed against my chest.
It sat beside me,
quiet,
almost companionable.

I noticed small things then—
a bird resting without fear,
grass growing where nothing was planted,
the way the horizon widened
without asking me to follow.

These were not signs of healing.
They were invitations.
And for once,
I did not refuse.

I stayed cautious.
Seeds that open too early
do not survive the cold.
So I allowed hope
to remain hypothetical,
something I acknowledged
without touching.

Still,
when I placed my hands on the ground,
I felt it—
not certainty,
not joy,
but readiness.

The kind that does not rush forward,
only loosens the soil
enough to breathe.

If healing comes,
it will not be loud.
It will arrive disguised
as ordinary days,
as moments that do not hurt,
as silence that no longer feels like exile.

For now,
this is enough—
to know that beneath the weight of everything,
the earth has not closed completely.

It is listening.`,
    theme: "",
    year: "2024",
