    id: 272,
    title: "I never wanted to reach you.",
    excerpt:
      "Only to exist close enough / to know you were real. / Like standing beside a river",
    full: `Only to exist close enough
to know you were real.

Like standing beside a river
with no intention of crossing—
listening,
because some waters are meant
to be understood,
not entered.

You were never mine,
and I never tried to change that.
There are connections
that survive
only because they remain untouched.

I learned you slowly,
the way morning learns the sky—
without urgency,
without questions,
without a name.

We were never a moment
others could recognize.
No beginning worth announcing,
no ending worth mourning.
Only a quiet continuity,
moving like seasons
that do not explain themselves.

When I think of you,
there is no longing.
Only awareness—
a gentle reminder
that depth exists
even in distance.

You passed through my thoughts
like wind through an open room,
never staying,
yet leaving the air altered.

I did not imagine a future with you.
I imagined stillness.
And in that stillness,
your presence rested
without demand.

Some feelings are not meant
to become louder.
They are meant
to remain intact—
unclaimed,
unquestioned.

You were a sentence
I never finished,
because it felt complete
as it was.

And if our paths never return
to the same horizon,
nothing will be lost.
What existed between us
was never fragile.

It was simply this—
two lives briefly aware
of each other’s light,
continuing forward,
unchanged,
yet quietly illuminated.`,
